    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "This market will resolve to “Yes” if the Government of Ukraine publicly agrees to a U.S.-approved peace framework for the Russo–Ukrainian war, by November 27, 2025, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nTo qualify, the agreement must be explicitly described as Ukraine’s formal acceptance of either (1) the U.S. 28-point peace plan, or (2) a revised or alternative peace framework that the United States publicly states it has approved. \n\nIf such an agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to “Yes”, regardless of if/when the agreement is implemented, enters into force, or is fully carried out.\n\nCounter proposals by Ukraine, agreements to “treat the U.S. framework as a basis”, “work within the framework” or other ambiguous statements will not qualify unless they are clearly described by both sides or a consensus of credible reporting as Ukraine’s formal acceptance of a U.S.-approved peace framework. \n\nThe primary resolution source for this market will be a consensus of credible reporting.",
    "outcome": "No",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nThe proposed US-approved peace plan for Ukraine was ultimately not agreed to by Ukraine by the November 28, 2025 deadline. Initial market optimism surged on November 24 following reports of US and Ukrainian officials making progress in talks, leading to a peak in prediction markets. However, the optimism was swiftly undermined by Ukraine's strong reservations about the plan's terms and deep skepticism regarding Russia's commitment to peace, leading to a rejection of the proposed framework.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2025-11-21:** Draft of a US-backed peace proposal emerges, putting pressure on Ukraine to accept terms or face a loss of US support [art_general_20251121_019_48a80c44], [art_general_20251121_015_a88bbbad].\n- **2025-11-24:** US and Ukrainian officials report progress in peace talks, causing market sentiment to peak sharply as a deal seems imminent [art_general_20251124_010_df6228ae].\n- **2025-11-25:** Optimism wanes as Ukrainian President Zelensky publicly breaks with US President Trump's assessment, expressing strong doubts that Putin wants peace and highlighting unresolved \"sensitive issues\" [art_politics_20251125_005_78a7c9ef]. Russia also effectively dismisses the framework [art_politics_20251125_002_10f905a3].\n- **2025-11-28:** The deadline passes without Ukraine agreeing to the US-approved peace plan.\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe outcome was driven by a fundamental misalignment between the proposed US-brokered peace terms and Ukraine's security requirements. Initially, the introduction of a concrete US plan created the appearance of momentum, which triggered the sharp market peak on November 24 [art_general_20251124_010_df6228ae]. However, this momentum stalled because the plan did not adequately address Ukraine's core concerns. Zelensky's deep-seated distrust of Russian President Vladimir Putin's intentions [art_politics_20251125_005_78a7c9ef] and the view that the plan overly favored Russian interests (described by some US officials as a \"wish list\" for Russia [art_general_20251123_022_ec8da5f5]) caused Ukraine to pull back. Furthermore, Russia's simultaneous dismissal of the framework [art_politics_20251125_002_10f905a3] effectively killed any remaining viability, leading to the final outcome of no agreement by the deadline.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nThe primary force pushing toward an agreement was the immense pressure exerted by the United States, which tied continued support to Ukraine's willingness to negotiate [art_general_20251121_015_a88bbbad]. The US even offered a 15-year security guarantee to sweeten the deal [art_politics_20251125_006_739305da]. However, this pressure was ultimately overwhelmed by Ukraine's assessment that the terms were too detrimental to its sovereignty and long-term security, coupled with a lack of credible commitment from Russia.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1\n    - title: Market peaks on perceived progress in US-Ukraine peace talks\n    - date: 2025-11-24\n    - why it matters causally: Created the highest expectation of a positive resolution before subsequent events reversed the trend.\n    - source article IDs: [art_general_20251124_010_df6228ae]\n- E2\n    - title: Zelensky publicly doubts Putin's desire for peace, stalling momentum\n    - date: 2025-11-25\n    - why it matters causally: Demonstrated Ukraine's fundamental unwillingness to accept the premise of the US plan without stronger guarantees.\n    - source article IDs: [art_politics_20251125_005_78a7c9ef]\n- E3\n    - title: Russia dismisses the US-Ukraine peace framework\n    - date: 2025-11-25\n    - why it matters causally: Removed any remaining possibility of a bilateral agreement, solidifying the negative outcome.\n    - source article IDs: [art_politics_20251125_002_10f905a3]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Progress in peace talks peaks market optimism | [art_general_20251124_010_df6228ae] | 2025-11-24 | 0.9 | Matches the turning point data. |\n| Zelensky doubts Putin wants peace | [art_politics_20251125_005_78a7c9ef] | 2025-11-25 | 1.0 | Clear public statement breaking with US optimism. |\n| Russia dismisses framework | [art_politics_20251125_002_10f905a3] | 2025-11-25 | 0.9 | Shows the deal was unworkable from both sides. |\n| US pressure and security guarantees | [art_general_20251121_015_a88bbbad], [art_politics_20251125_006_739305da] | 2025-11-21, 2025-11-25 | 0.9 | Context for the negotiations. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThe main alternative path would have materialized if the US had offered stronger, immediate guarantees (such as accelerated NATO membership) that overcame Ukraine's security fears, or if Russia had made credible, public concessions. However, the deep mistrust and maximalist positions on both sides made this highly improbable within the tight timeframe.\n",
