    "id": "polymarket_0x386813cf90074b5b5bc274d145be89a20f07386a3f8a7d370781a0af7196dc25",
    "title": "Will South Korean President Lee Jae-myung be impeached during 2025?",
    "question_type": "binary",
    "options": [
      "Yes",
      "No"
    ],
    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if the President of South Korea, Lee Jae-myung, is formally impeached by the South Korean National Assembly by December 31, 2025, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No.\"\n\nFor this market to resolve to \"Yes\" it is only necessary that the National Assembly propose and approve a motion of impeachment against Lee Jae-myung, regardless of whether the Constitutional Court later upholds the impeachment.\n\nThe primary resolution source for this market is official information from the South Korean government, however a consensus of credible reporting may be used.",
    "outcome": "No",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nSouth Korean President Lee Jae-myung was not impeached during 2025. Following the turbulent impeachment and removal of his predecessor Yoon Suk Yeol earlier in the year, Lee assumed office under significant political scrutiny. Despite opposition challenges and various political controversies during his initial months in office, Lee managed to consolidate his base and maintain sufficient parliamentary support to avoid any formal impeachment proceedings. The threshold for impeachment remained unmet, leading to his survival throughout the year.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2025-04-28**: Following the impeachment of Yoon Suk Yeol, Lee Jae-myung secures his position and prepares for his term [art_general_20250428_017_dd5cff25].\n- **2025-06-15**: Early challenges to Lee's administration begin to surface, but his Democratic Party maintains a firm grip on the legislative agenda [art_politics_20250615_002_203c164a].\n- **2025-09-15**: A flurry of political debates and minor controversies occur, but none reach the level of impeachable offenses [art_politics_20250915_002_5ec2723c], [art_politics_20250915_016_0ceb0e62].\n- **2025-10-10**: The opposition's attempts to mobilize public sentiment against Lee fail to gain sufficient traction [art_politics_20251010_002_aab8c034].\n- **2025-12-18**: Lee successfully concludes the legislative year without any formal impeachment motions being introduced [art_general_20251218_007_df596546].\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe outcome of Lee Jae-myung not being impeached resulted from several key factors. First, the political fatigue following the recent impeachment of Yoon Suk Yeol caused an environment where both the public and politicians were hesitant to pursue another major disruption [art_general_20250428_017_dd5cff25]. This hesitancy led to a higher political threshold for any opposition actions against Lee. Second, Lee's administration proactively managed emerging controversies, preventing them from escalating into constitutional crises [art_politics_20250915_002_5ec2723c]. Finally, the opposition lacked the required supermajority in the National Assembly, and failed to build a compelling narrative that would trigger cross-party defection, which ultimately resulted in the absence of any impeachment motion [art_politics_20251010_002_aab8c034].\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nThe primary countervailing factor was the ongoing polarization of South Korean politics, with conservative factions aggressively targeting Lee's past legal issues and administration missteps. However, these efforts were overwhelmed by Lee's strong legislative backing and the overarching public desire for stability after the previous administration's collapse.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1\n  - title: Post-Yoon political stabilization\n  - date: 2025-04-28 to 2025-06-15\n  - why it matters causally: Established the baseline stability that insulated Lee from early shocks.\n  - source article IDs: [art_general_20250428_017_dd5cff25], [art_politics_20250615_002_203c164a]\n- E2\n  - title: Mid-year political controversies managed\n  - date: 2025-09-15\n  - why it matters causally: Prevented isolated issues from snowballing into impeachment grounds.\n  - source article IDs: [art_politics_20250915_002_5ec2723c], [art_politics_20250915_016_0ceb0e62]\n- E3\n  - title: Opposition fails to mobilize\n  - date: 2025-10-10\n  - why it matters causally: Demonstrated the lack of political capital to launch an impeachment drive.\n  - source article IDs: [art_politics_20251010_002_aab8c034]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Post-Yoon stabilization | art_general_20250428_017_dd5cff25, art_politics_20250615_002_203c164a | 2025-04 to 2025-06 | 0.9 | High confidence in stabilization period. |\n| Management of controversies | art_politics_20250915_002_5ec2723c, art_politics_20250915_016_0ceb0e62 | 2025-09 | 0.85 | Clear mitigation of minor crises. |\n| Opposition failure | art_politics_20251010_002_aab8c034 | 2025-10 | 0.9 | Opposition lacked momentum. |\n| Year-end survival | art_general_20251218_007_df596546 | 2025-12 | 1.0 | Definitive proof of non-impeachment in 2025. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThe main uncertainty was whether any sudden, massive scandal (similar to what triggered Yoon's downfall) might emerge. An alternative path would have seen the opposition successfully reviving Lee's previous legal controversies (e.g., development scandals) to sway public opinion and secure enough votes for a motion, but this did not materialize.\n",
    "is_polymarket": true,
    "is_overlap": false,
